<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="RSV_Developer_Guide"></a> RSV Developer Guide </span></h2>
<p />
<p />
This is a guide for developers who are creating new RSV metrics or who are maintaining existing RSV metrics. 
<p />
<h3><a name="Overview"></a> Overview </h3>
<p />
RSV is an infrastructure we use in Open Science Grid for monitoring the grid-aspects of OSG. For example, we use it to verify that a site is correctly accepting jobs to run, but we don't use it to monitor the fan speed on computers in your cluster. 
<p />
The RSV software is broken into three portions:
<p /> <ol>
<li> <strong>RSV Core</strong> <br>The RSV core is the underlying infrastructure that is used to run the set of metrics (tests) performed by RSV.  This includes Condor-Cron and the <code>rsv-control</code> tool.
</li> <li> <strong>RSV Metrics</strong> <br> The RSV metrics are the set of tests that RSV performs. 
</li> <li> <strong>RSV Consumers</strong> <br>The RSV consumers publish the results of the metrics.  Examples are the <code>html-consumer</code> which creates a local web page for site administrators to view, and the <code>gratia-consumer</code> which uploads records to the GOC.
</li></ol> 
<p />
You are most likely to be concerned with adding or maintaining some of the RSV metrics. 
<p /> <ul>
<li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/RsvOwners" class="twikiLink">List of RSV Metrics and their owners</a>
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h3><a name="Your_responsibilities_as_a_metri"></a> Your responsibilities as a metric developer </h3>
<p /> <ul>
<li> You will write and/or maintain the metric.
</li> <li> You will inform the VDT and OSG Software Tools Group if you no longer have the effort to maintain your metrics.
</li> <li> You will test your metric before you declare it ready for release. 
</li> <li> When the VDT team is unable to answer questions or provide support about your RSV metric, we'll ask you for help to do the support. 
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h3><a name="OSG_Software_s_responsibilities"></a> OSG Software's responsibilities as the RSV maintainer </h3>
<p /> <ul>
<li> OSG Software maintains the source code repository for RSV, and provides access to it. (We use Subversion.)
</li> <li> If you need access to computers on which to test your probes, the VDT will give you access to it's test cluster.
</li> <li> The OSG Software will coordinate the release process with the VTB and ITB.
</li> <li> The OSG Software will release new versions of RSV. 
</li> <li> The OSG Software will be the first line of support for RSV--the core and metrics
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h3><a name="What_you_need_to_know"></a> What you need to know </h3>
<p /> <ul>
<li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/RsvPrinciples" class="twikiLink">RSV Principles</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/RsvArchitecture" class="twikiLink">RSV Architecture</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/WriteYourOwnRSVProbe" class="twikiLink">How to write, install, and test an RSV probe</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/RsvRepoAccess" class="twikiLink">How to access the RSV source code repository</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/ReleaseMethodology" class="twikiLink">How the source code repository and release process are managed</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/Release3/RsvSupport" class="twikiLink">How RSV support works, and your role in it</a>
</li></ul> 
<p />
